        "type": "text",
        "text": "Perfect! ✅ Your counter circuit is ready. Here's the summary:\n\n### **Wiring Table**\n| Arduino Pin | Component | Pin Role | Purpose |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| D2 | Display segment A | via R_A (220Ω) | Top segment |\n| D3 | Display segment B | via R_B (220Ω) | Top-right segment |\n| D4 | Display segment C | via R_C (220Ω) | Middle-right segment |\n| D5 | Display segment D | via R_D (220Ω) | Bottom segment |\n| D6 | Display segment E | via R_E (220Ω) | Bottom-left segment |\n| D7 | Display segment F | via R_F (220Ω) | Top-left segment |\n| D8 | Display segment G | via R_G (220Ω) | Middle segment |\n| D9 | BTN_UP | pin A | Increment button (INPUT_PULLUP) |\n| D10 | BTN_DOWN | pin A | Decrement button (INPUT_PULLUP) |\n| GND | Display + Buttons | GND rails | Common ground |\n\n### **How It Works**\n- Pressing **BTN_UP** (D9) increments the counter; stays at 9 if already there.\n- Pressing **BTN_DOWN** (D10) decrements the counter; stays at 0 if already there.\n- The sketch uses `displayDigit()` to drive segment patterns for digits 0–9 via if/else logic.\n- Buttons use `INPUT_PULLUP` with edge detection (LOW→HIGH transition = press event).\n- 20ms debounce delay after each button press prevents jitter.\n\n### **Power Budget**\n- **Per-segment**: 220Ω resistors limit each segment to (5V / 220Ω) ≈ 23 mA max (safe).\n- **Active segments per digit**: 6–7 segments lit simultaneously ≈ 140–160 mA worst-case.\n- **Buttons**: negligible draw (pull-up resistor internal, ~100 µA).\n- **Total board draw**: ~165 mA peak (within Uno's 500 mA USB and ~400 mA regulator capacity). ✅\n\nThe circuit is ready to upload!"
